bug.short_desc: Initial issues and thoughts of qx.Website

long_desc.thetext:
Hey, Thanks for taking the time to review qx.Website. Thats great and you have some really good points.
String Formating -------------- This is a good point and we should definitely open up a separate bug for that. We could fix the current implementation we have and add it to qx.website. But the policy still stands. We only add methods to native types to get those types up to a certain standard. This is also true for Function.bind [1]. Still, qx.Website also has already some other non standard helpers where we could add the format function easily.
XHR --- Our XHR implementation is pretty basic by now. It only offers the API of XHL level2 which is a native API. Sure, there is room for improvement on top of that. This could also be a good candidate for a separate bug. :)
Show/hide --------- Really good point. Should be added as well as bug report.
Usage of Class structures --------------------- We need to do some experiments in that area ourself. I'm not sure if the current define is enough / too much or the right tool at all to get a good structured code. Bringing the data binding to qx.Website will sure give use some more experience about the general structure as well. We are also missing a demo of how to use the plugin API which might be another point of how we could get a good feeling of whats feeling right and wrong.
qx.lang & Policy ------------- We already have a bug for cleaning up all the stuff we have in that area (#6151). This is a grown part of the framework and a cleanup is necessary to get every component up to date. But as already mentioned, the policy will stay the same.
Custom builds ------------ The current way is to use a website skeleton and modify the Q_INCLUDES list as you have suggested. But sure thats not a comfortable way. We are aware of this and already have some plans who to make it more comfortable. But we don't have much more than ideas so I can't tell you much about it.
Part loading ---------- As for parts, you will always need the generator to create them. Maybe we could manage to get something similar done without the need of the generator. But thats a challenge! Maybe we try require.js or something else. I don't know jet but thats sure one thing we should take care of.
jQuery plugins ------------ It's interesting that you bring up this topic because we have talked about that from some time now and agree with you. I should be somehow possible to use the huge amount of already existing plugins from the jQuery world. We are also working on that. ;)
All in all, seems like you have a good sens of what needs to be done to advance with qx.Website, or at least same same sens as we have. ;) Do you want to open the separate bugs I mentioned above to be the reporter and get the updates or should I go ahead and open them?
[1] https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Function/bind

Hi, Martin.
Surely I will open those bugs. But I need to clarify before:
1) String formatting. Should I open bug for adding qx.lang.String.format to q.string? Or for changing qx.lang.String.format implementation? Or two bugs for both? ;-)
2) XHR. Here I think it would be good to have kind of "coalesce" arguments (default true property is better) which qx.io.remote.Rpc has, to effectively have two events "completed" and "failed". What do you think?
3) Show/hide. Simple case is clear.
q("#warning").setStyle("display", "none"); q("#warning").setStyle("display", "block");
goes
q("#warning").hide(); q("#warning").show();
But as I've just thought it'll have a conflict with qx.ui.core.Widget's naming, its "exclude" acts like this q("#warning").hide(), and "hide" is about "visibility" style. So it's getting less clear, and it's good to rethink considering full qx.ui.core.Widget's show/hide/exclude/isVisible/isHidden/isExcluded and Sizzle's ":visible" pseudo-class.
I understand about class structures. About Function.bind, yes, I was wrong, I've missed it out by some reason. About Q_INCLUDES, it's not that bad, at least it's direct.
About part loading. Oh, personally I don't think it's good idea to add another script loader. If user wants to load scripts on-demand, split into files manually why not to use q.io.script? All that advanced functionality provided by generator, which takes care of splitting, dependencies, sizes, etc, is working well. Moreover it's automatic, when parts are defined, being close to define once and forget, at least in my qx.Desktop experience. Yes, it adds some complexity but the trade-off with functionality is common.
And about jQuery plugins, yeah, that's just rational ;-)

1) I would suggest two bugs so we could mark one depending on the other. We should add a proper API to q and not a API we want to change anyway. :)
2) I would use the same convenience we already have in the qx.io. layer wich offers a success event e.g.
3) Thats a good point and should go into the bug as well. While taking care of that issue, we should figure out what to add and how.
Thanks. :)
Created attachment 1171 Proof-of-concept implementation of jquery adapter

Since I had time yesterday, I've been experimenting with jQuery adapter for the q. I manged final version to be a plain qx class.
What is interesting about it is jQuery tests. So changing original library to the q and adapter, it's possible to try make them pass (tests/index.html). Partially passed cases could show differences in implementation (e.g. script tag of q.create and $). Completely failed cases show either missing methods (prepend, prependTo, wrap*, andSelf, end, so question here is whether qx.module.Manipulating and qx.bom.Collection should have same capabilities), or different/wrong implementation (all dimension cases failed, even though methods are passed through, ":visible,:hidden" selectors failed but I guess Sizzle supports it, etc.). So it might be interesting even regardless of jQuery subset support.
Some recent issues I've remembered I put in index.html. Not sure what to do with them, bug report?
Also I've found layers of jQuery that probably shouldn't, or at least hard to port. One is an animation, which I guess isn't related to CSS Animation at all. Event layer I'm not sure of. $.data and networking are commonly used, but I doubt they could mapped to the q, if only re-implemented with the q. The core layer is pretty probable to support at middle-to-high level.

(In reply to comment #6) > Since I had time yesterday, I've been experimenting with jQuery adapter for the > q. I manged final version to be a plain qx class.
Wow, that is impressive! We keep our development regarding the jQuery compatibility under the hood in a separate branch. https://github.com/qooxdoo/qooxdoo/tree/jqx If you check out the recent commits, you will see that our approach will be a bit different. :) What do you think about it?
> What is interesting about it is jQuery tests. So changing original library to > the q and adapter, it's possible to try make them pass (tests/index.html). > Partially passed cases could show differences in implementation (e.g. script > tag of q.create and $). Completely failed cases show either missing methods > (prepend, prependTo, wrap*, andSelf, end, so question here is whether > qx.module.Manipulating and qx.bom.Collection should have same capabilities), or > different/wrong implementation (all dimension cases failed, even though methods > are passed through, ":visible,:hidden" selectors failed but I guess Sizzle > supports it, etc.). So it might be interesting even regardless of jQuery subset > support.
The qx.bom.Collection will be deprecated and removed anyway. So checking this is not worth the effort. ;)
> Some recent issues I've remembered I put in index.html. Not sure what to do > with them, bug report? Well, I would say we can close it because you filed all the single issues (thanks for that btw.)! We can also continue some discussion via mail if you would like to collaborate.
> Also I've found layers of jQuery that probably shouldn't, or at least hard to > port. One is an animation, which I guess isn't related to CSS Animation at all. > Event layer I'm not sure of. $.data and networking are commonly used, but I > doubt they could mapped to the q, if only re-implemented with the q. The core > layer is pretty probable to support at middle-to-high level.
Yes, thats also one thing we also found out. Events and animation are too different to port.

> If you check out the recent commits, you will see that our approach will be a > bit different. :) What do you think about it?
What I see, for example, in https://github.com/qooxdoo/qooxdoo/commit/6c169a494129663d04e60a72afbb0f3f4d9ffe33, makes me think I don't understand something.
As far as I see, there are two ways of using the q, concerning jQuery:
1) When the q is sufficient (no 3rd party software required, like in ToDo app). The q facades the power of qx.bom.*, qx.dom.*, etc. with its high-level chained API.
2) When the q is not sufficient, and user wants a jQuery plugin. He adds small (relative to the q's size) plugin to provide jQuery compatibility. But all implementation is still replies on qx.bom.*, qx.dom.*, etc.
If it's necessary to include jQuery to use the q, isn't it going to be a jQuery plugin providing functionality on top of it? With current jQuery size it'll double the footprint. Why use external implementation with there's already an internal one. If jQuery is included then plugins can use it directly, no compatibility issue. So I must be missing some point here.
> The qx.bom.Collection will be deprecated and removed anyway. So checking this > is not worth the effort.
What's wrong with qx.bom.Collection? As I see qx.bom.Collection and qx.module.Manipulating provide the same functionality using same primitives. But qx.bom.Collection provides most of jQuery manipulation API, whereas qx.module.Manipulating provides somewhat about a half of. Why re-implementing it, not just using qx.bom.Collection in qx.module.Manipulating?
>> Some recent issues I've remembered I put in index.html. Not sure what to do >> with them, bug report? > Well, I would say we can close it because you filed all the single issues.
Here I meant the new issues with the q. As such q.getNext() returning [null], exception thrown querying ":visible/:hidden" selectors (not related to show/hide shortcuts), treating of Text nodes and Comment nodes by the q. Should I report them separately, report at once, or not report?
> We can also continue some discussion via mail if you > would like to collaborate.
I would like to.

(In reply to comment #8) > What I see, for example, in > https://github.com/qooxdoo/qooxdoo/commit/6c169a494129663d04e60a72afbb0f3f4d9ffe33, > makes me think I don't understand something. > > As far as I see, there are two ways of using the q, concerning jQuery: > > 1) When the q is sufficient (no 3rd party software required, like in ToDo app). > The q facades the power of qx.bom.*, qx.dom.*, etc. with its high-level chained > API. > > 2) When the q is not sufficient, and user wants a jQuery plugin. He adds small > (relative to the q's size) plugin to provide jQuery compatibility. But all > implementation is still replies on qx.bom.*, qx.dom.*, etc. > > If it's necessary to include jQuery to use the q, isn't it going to be a jQuery > plugin providing functionality on top of it? With current jQuery size it'll > double the footprint. Why use external implementation with there's already an > internal one. If jQuery is included then plugins can use it directly, no > compatibility issue. So I must be missing some point here.
We plan it to have the other way around. Including jQuery makes us 100% jQuery compatible without any work. We don't need to fake any API or check out every new release and reimplement all the features. Additionally, on a long term, we can get rid of the code we have, which is already in jQuery. This reduces maintanence work for us in the core team. And btw. parts of the bom code is an old copy of jQuery anyway.
> What's wrong with qx.bom.Collection? As I see qx.bom.Collection and > qx.module.Manipulating provide the same functionality using same primitives. > But qx.bom.Collection provides most of jQuery manipulation API, whereas > qx.module.Manipulating provides somewhat about a half of. Why re-implementing > it, not just using qx.bom.Collection in qx.module.Manipulating?
The produced file size. Creating a js file containing qx.bom.Collection pulls in a lot of other classes and ends in a file about 600kb big. You can't compete with such a file size when jQuery does have 93kb. And the general architecture of qx.bom.Collection does not allow to modularize and thats why we took a step back and started from scratch with a scalable architecture which ended in q.
> Here I meant the new issues with the q. As such q.getNext() returning [null], > exception thrown querying ":visible/:hidden" selectors (not related to > show/hide shortcuts), treating of Text nodes and Comment nodes by the q. Should > I report them separately, report at once, or not report? Yes, report everything you find as a separate bug report. Thats a great way to help us get the library good. If you are interested, clone the qooxdoo repo and supply pull requests with the fixes we can integrate easily. Are you familiar with the infrastructure in the framework and how to build the lib yourself?
> > We can also continue some discussion via mail if you > > would like to collaborate. > > I would like to. Then we should continue the discussion in private mails. Just mail me a martin.wittemann@1und1.de
I mark this bug as WORKSFORME because we started the initial discussion and figured out what the separate single bugs are. The ongoing discussion will be offline.
Closed all bugs already shipped with a release.
